Patient is 55 years old and presented to the emergency department for evaluation of chest discomfort.  He said yesterday he was doing minimal work he was on the back of his truck and drinking when he felt his heart racing and some chest tightness and he was short of breath.  He was seen black-and-white he thought he was going to pass out.  He sat down and it was ongoing for 45 minutes to roughly an hour.  He did mention some right shoulder discomfort.  He was seen in the emergency department.  His EKG showed sinus rhythm ST depressions noted but no ST elevations were seen.  His initial troponin was 19 in the subsequent troponin was 105.4.  By the time he was in the ER he was completely symptom-free.  Overnight he has not had any chest discomfort either.  He had mentioned that over the last 1 month going up a flight of stairs he would be short of breath.  He has had always some chest tightness going on for years and he did not notice any worsening.  He had mentioned also that over the last few weeks they have been working up a soft tissue mass in the right upper neck and even had recent MRI of the chest which was otherwise unremarkable.  In the emergency department CT of the brain was performed which was essentially unremarkable.  CTA of the chest was also performed which showed no evidence of acute pulmonary embolism.  No coronary artery calcification.   Risk factor assessment for CAD He states he has hypercholesterolemia has been on medicines for 30 years At one point was hypertensive but diet controlled He was a smoker but quit 20 years ago There is a family history and a brother had a myocardial infarction at 45 years old.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I've had minor and easily manageable tinnitus in the past, usually not even noticeable.  I had been extremely excited to get the vaccine.  Unfortunately, about 2 weeks after the 1st Pfizer vaccine, I started having tinnitus very severely.  I was desperately trying to find treatments online on Tuesday night April 6 and stumbled across a social media page entitled (Privacy).  At the time there were maybe 300 members on that site, which has now been renamed to (Privacy) and has 2,800 members!  At that point I knew that that was my issue and decided NOT to get the second shot the next day.  It was so severe that I could not risk getting worse.  I could not concentrate, could barely sleep, was very tense, etc.  After (1) reading that while some people got worse after the second shot, many did not see any change, and (2) since I wanted very badly to be fully vaccinated for ease of travel in the future, and (3) since my tinnitus seemed to improve slightly approximately April 12-16, I went ahead and got the second dose.  Since then it got way worse, but then there were better days, too.  As I write this on July 16 at around 2:30am, it has been way way worse since approximately July 7th or 8th.  The social media page seems to suggest Tinnitus can be affected by diet.  I wonder if climate also affects it??  Last week I was in drier climates and I was fine; since my return to my more humid home, it has been the WORST EVER!!
LAB_DATA: none
OTHER_MEDS: low dose lisinipril, as needed.  Nutrilite double X and other supplements

Was almost totally incapacitated -- couldn't get up from chair, toilet, or bed, couldn't sleep in bed because of pain, needed help getting dressed, couldn't go up and down stairs, couldn't drive, couldn't do normal household chores, extreme fatigue. Doctor ordered lab work and determined I had Polymyalgia Rheumatica -- which I never had before.  Never had any rheumatic disease.  She prescribed 15 mg daily Predisone and Hydrocodone.  Within two days, symptoms eased considerably.  After taking for two weeks, much improvement so she had me cut Predisone to 10 mg; however, symptoms began coming back.  So back on 15 mgs. again.  Now, two weeks later, symptoms are basically gone.  Talked to doctor again today.  She is having me cut back on Prednisone more slowly -- only 1 mg at a time over a longer period.  My left hip started bothering me approximately on March 1, 2021.  By the first part of May, it had spread to all the parts of my body listed above.  I contacted doctor approximately on 6/1/2021 and started taking Predisone.  I talked to her again 6/11/2021 and 7/15/2021.

Thursday around mid- day again I continued to have nausea and dizziness, then I also started having chest tightness, I used my albuterol inhaler which is new to me for allergy induced asthma, which helped. Saturday I was beginning to feel better until mid afternoon I had a different chest discomfort and nausea and I reported to the emergency room they ruled out a cardiac event, gave me 2 baby aspirin and zofran and sent me home.  Sunday I woke up with a terrible migraine I treated with alternating tylenol and ibuprofen for about 24 hours.  Monday- Tuesday- Wednesday I just felt worn out, fatigued over all not well.  Thursday I finally started feeling better and contiue dto feel better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient was sitting in a chair in our waiting room as we request after a vaccine with her soon to be mother in law.  After about 5 or 10 minutes her mother in law said shes not feeling well to my technician who was visible from her seat.  He called me to her and I went to help.  The patient put her head back while she was seated and stated that she wasn't feeling well and was breaking out in a sweat. She then stated her vision was blurry and felt like she was going to throw up. I had my technician call 911.  I asked her if she thought she would feel better if she put her head between her legs and she refused stating that she would throw up.  We kept her in the chair while her eyes opened and closed and kept talking to her to keep her responsive.  She asked for water so we got her a cold bottle and we held it against her forehead which she said made her feel better.  After approximately 5 minutes she totally snapped out of it. She wanted a drink of the cold water and I advised her to take small sips.  Then two gentleman arrived from the ambulance crew and checked her bp which was normal.  They offered to take her to the hospital to get checked but she refused.
LAB_DATA: Patients blood pressure was checked by the ambulance crew and found to be normal.  Patient refused any further treatment

SYMPTOM_TEXT: In May patient noticed progressive painful lower extremity edema (left greater than right). On June 11, patient came to the hospital with sudden onset dyspnea, palpitations, lightheadedness and dizziness while refereeing a basketball game. Ultrasound of lower extremities found non-occlusive thrombus in the left common and profunda femoral veins/occlusive thrombus throughout the left femoral vein/popliteal vein, and tibioperoneal trunk. Patient started on heparin drip and admitted to stepdown unit for concern of submassive PE given elevated BNP, DVTs, and dyspnea, and confirmed via VQ scan. Patient was transitioned to oral anticoagulation (apixaban). Swelling of legs greatly improved, and dyspnea improved though cough persistent by the time of discharge. Of note, patient also has a history of elevated PSA (to 80s), but patient has not seen urology for follow-up for possible malignancy. Patient also found to have UTI (klebsiella) secondary to his chronic urinary retention.
LAB_DATA: PSA on 7/15: 106.752  CT abdomen/pelvis 7/14: IMPRESSION: 1.  Interval progression of left hydronephrosis and renal atrophy. Left ureter and collecting system cannot be completely evaluated secondary to partial opacification. There is concentric smooth wall thickening of the left ureter through most of its length likely from chronic infection. A few filling defects in the left renal collecting system probably represent infected or hemorrhagic debris, with consider evaluation of this with direct visualization if there is a possibility clinically of malignancy. 2.  Interval worsening of bladder wall thickening and trabeculations with irregular lobulated mucosal surfaces which could be in the setting of chronic cystitis or detrusor hypertrophy. Underlying malignancy would be difficult to exclude for which cystoscopy is recommended. 3.  Punctate nonobstructing right kidney stone.  7/13 Perfusion scan: IMPRESSION: High probability of pulmonary embolism.
HISTORY: chronic urinary retention, traumatic brain injury, chronic kidney disease stage 3, possible malignancy of prostate/bladder that has not been worked up

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At approximately 7:00pm on 7/7/2021, I started to show signs of an anaphylaxis reaction. Those include: lip swelling, facial swelling, moderate difficulty breathing, anxiety, and severe diarrhea. Since it was late in the evening, I treated with an Albuterol inhaler, which provided very little relief. On 7/8/2021, I went to Urgent Care and was given a course of Prednisone, starting at 60mg and tapering down. Lip and facial swelling and diarrhea continued to be moderate to severe. On 7/9/2021, my breathing condition improved while still on 60mg of Prednisone. Facial and lip swelling continued. Additional diarrhea continued, but not as severe. On Sunday, 7/11/2021, as I reduced to 40mg of Prednisone, my condition deteriorated starting at 10:00am. Facial and lip swelling worsened, there was quite a bit of difficulty breathing and more diarrhea. However, I started to feel a lump in my throat as well. An on-call nurse asked me to take 25mg of Benadryl-- which I did. On 7/11/2021 at approximately 3:00pm, I went to the Emergency Room. O2 Sat levels ranged from 88 % to 95% and my BP was in the normal range. At 5:00pm, I was given additional Prednisone orally to increase that daily does to 60mg. I remain on a tapering dose today-- at 40mg and decending.
LAB_DATA: None noted.
OTHER_MEDS: Fluticasone Propionate x2/day; Losartan-Hydrochlorothiazide 50-12.5 mg per tablet x1/day; Famotidine 40 mg tablet x1/day; Pantoprazole 40 mg tablet x1/day; Levocetirizine 5 mg Tablet x1/day; Trazodone 50 mg tablet x2 tabs/day; B-complex wit
ALLERGIES: Aspirin - difficulty breathing; Peanuts - anaphylaxis; Shellfish - anaphylaxis; Bee Stings - late phase anaphylaxis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 07-15-21 we had a nurse vaccinating for Pfizer at one table and a nurse vaccinating for Janssen at another table. Each table keeps their vaccines in color coordinated boxes that is assigned for each vaccine being administered. At approximately 12:20PM the nurse who was vaccinating Janssen closed her pink box labeled J&J and stepped away 6 feet from her table to speak to the service representative that was checking in our patients. Unbeknownst to us, the nurse vaccinating Pfizer walked to the other table and grabbed vaccines from the pink box labeled J&J and took them back to her station and put them into her clear box. There were a total of 2 vaccines taken from the Janssen box. At approximately 12:45PM the nurse vaccinating Janssen returned to her table and noticed that two vaccines were missing from her box. The other nurse then proceed to give her one back. The nurse vaccinating Janssen immediately brought the syringes to a supervisor for disposal. Based on the timeline we have compiled a list of patients that were vaccinated by the nurse who took the Janssen vaccines. Patient was to receive his second dose of Pfizer but now based on the above instance we are unsure if he was given Janssen. Administration has been made aware of the instance and one of our MDs notified the patient.
